<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Directors guided on insider trade law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Stock Exchange-sponsored committee will today issue a code of conduct
telling company directors they should no longer privately correct individual
analysts' profit forecasts, but must instead inform the entire market of
such price-sensitive information.
Institutional investors and stockbrokers who receive unpublished price
sensitive information will also be advised to encourage companies to publish
the information widely.
The new code has been drawn up so that companies, shareholders and
stockbrokers can be confident that they can communicate with each other
without infringing the Criminal Justice Act provision on insider trading,
which will come into force next Tuesday.
The code has been drafted by a committee consisting of representatives of
the 100 Group of finance directors, the Institutional Fund Managers
Association and the Association of British Insurers.
A member of the committee said: 'It does spell out the circumstances under
which the companies should disclose information and points out that
dribbling out information is unacceptable.'
Among other things, the document discusses how company directors should deal
with analysts' earnings estimates which are wildly wrong. It will tell
companies that they are not required to correct a false impression by an
analyst. However, if a correction is given to the analyst, it must be
simultaneously communicated to the market as a whole.
A committee member said the committee was particularly concerned about
earnings forecasts from analysts who are employed by the company's own
stockbroker 'whose forecasts have been surprisingly accurate'.
</TEXT>
