<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Tories join attack on army job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was criticised by all parties at Westminster yesterday over a
new round of army redundancies.
Tory backbenchers joined MPs from the opposition parties to attack the 7,000
job losses made under the third phase of a cuts programme.
There was particular concern about the prospect of redundancies among
officers and other ranks serving in Bosnia.
Downing Street officials said last night that the number of compulsory
redundancies among troops in Bosnia would 'only just' run into double
figures. Redundancies would be 'across the board'. It would be the same for
troops in Ulster and elsewhere as it would be for those in Bosnia.
Mr Jeremy Hanley, armed forces minister, giving details of the cuts in a
parliamentary written answer, said there would be just over 1,000
redundancies. All those selected would be notified today.
Mr Winston Churchill, a Tory member of the cross-party Commons defence
committee, said: 'We are strongly opposed, on an all-party committee basis,
to these cuts.'
Mr David Clark, shadow defence secretary, said the government was 'badly
mismanaging British military forces'.
