<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Companies breach R&amp;D accounting standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A quarter of companies that refer to research-and-development expenditure in
their annual reports are breaching accounting standards, a survey of
financial reporting said yesterday.
From a sample of 300 companies, 148 disclose evidence of R&amp;D - usually in
the chairman's statement - but 25 per cent of these do not show the amount
they spend. Fourteen per cent of the 65 FT-SE 100 companies that spend on
R&amp;D do not disclose the amount.
This practice contradicts SSAP 13, the accounting standard on R&amp;D, which
demands disclosure of the amount split between spending in the current year
and that capitalised over future years.
The details emerge in Financial Reporting 1993-94, the annual survey of
company accounts produced by the Institute of Chartered Accountants in
England and Wales.
Mr David Tonkin, joint editor, said it was 'misleading' for companies to
state that they spent money on R&amp;D unless the amount was material. If it was
material, the amount should be disclosed.
The survey shows that reporting practice is beginning to be affected by the
changing accounting standards regime, especially FRS 3, the new standard on
the profit-and-loss account. It shows that the number of companies with
'extraordinary items' - abolished by the standard - fell from 52 per cent in
last year's survey to 26 per cent.
It also shows a slight increase in the number of accounts qualified or
prefaced by special comments from companies' auditors - rising from 4 per
cent to 6 per cent.
A chapter in the book describes existing regulations governing the
advertising of half-year reports as 'lamentable'.
It recommends that companies should be obliged to state whether they are
exempt from requirements of the Stock Exchange, and says that the report
should be dated.
The survey suggests that the reforms being undertaken by the Accounting
Standards Board are emphasising disclosure rather than tightly prescriptive
measurement.
Financial Reporting 1993-94. Accountancy Books, PO Box 620, Central Milton
Keynes, MK9 2JX. Pounds 55.
</TEXT>
