<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Government cuts insurance tax rate to 2.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday bowed to pressure from the insurance industry by
modifying the proposed tax on premiums and reducing its rate from 3 per cent
to 2.5 per cent.
The change will only marginally reduce the amount of money raised annually
from the tax, introduced in the November Budget - but the changes are
expected to yield administrative savings for insurance companies and were
widely welcomed by the industry.
Mr Tony Baker, deputy director-general of the Association of British
Insurers, said: 'It is much easier for everybody and good news for
policyholders.'
Following the changes, announced yesterday by Sir John Cope,
paymaster-general, the premium tax will be charged on insurance premiums on
a gross rather than a net basis - before, rather than after the deduction of
brokerage commission. The change will make the tax easier for insurance
companies to collect, and the rate has been lowered to reduce the extra
burden on insurers and their customers which would have resulted.
Sir John said: 'The reduction of the rate is directly linked to the decision
to tax gross rather than net premiums. We have been able to address the
concerns of the insurance industry about the operation of the new tax to
make it simpler and . . . its administration easier.'
The yield from the tax will now be about Pounds 760m in its first full year
rising to Pounds 835m in 1996-97. That compares with forecasts - calculated
on the basis of a 3 per cent rate - of Pounds 775m and Pounds 840m.
Sir John said the proposed changes met the insurance industry's requests
'for greater flexibility and for arrangements which tie in more closely with
existing systems'.
The change will have no impact on policyholders, who will still face average
increases of 35p per week on buildings, contents and motor insurance.
Mr Baker said the tax as originally proposed would have 'distorted'
competition between companies which sell direct to the public and those
which sell through brokers. Commission rates differ between types of
insurance, so the tax would also have been difficult to administer.
Mr Peter Foster, general manager, finance, of Commercial Union, the UK's
largest composite (general and life) insurance company, said: 'There is
still a danger that the rate of the tax could be increased, but obviously
people have been taking note of the representations the industry has made.'
Insurers will be able to account for the tax in line with existing
accounting procedures rather than on a 'cash receipts basis'. They will be
able to account for the tax quarterly rather than monthly as originally
proposed, and longer-term policies, for which a premium has already been
paid, will not be subject to the tax.
</TEXT>
