<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / TSB supports creation of PIA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TSB, the banking group, yesterday came out in support of the proposed
Personal Investment Authority and announced its plan to apply for membership
of the new regulator.
Elsewhere, doubts about the new authority were expressed by the Consumers'
Association which told the Commons Treasury committee that there should be a
shift to 'a simple, clear system of statutory regulation'.
The TSB move will be a welcome boost to the PIA, which faces continued
scepticism in the financial services industry. The authority must attract
substantial support in order to achieve credibility.
TSB said bringing all supervision and regulation of financial services for
personal customers under one body would make it easier to achieve higher and
more consistent standards. TSB's existing regulator is Lautro, the
self-regulating organisation for the life insurance industry.
In evidence to the MPs the Consumers' Association called for a new office of
director-general of investor protection, directly accountable to government
and parliament. The regulator would have statutory powers to make the
industry comply and would be funded by a statutory levy.
The association said a successful PIA would help to rationalise the current
regulatory structure but its effectiveness would be limited by the
continuing ability of individuals and companies in the sector to choose
their own regulator.
</TEXT>
