<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Single mothers on increase in Wales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than a third of births in Wales are to unmarried women, a rate which
has tripled in a decade, official figures showed yesterday.
The latest edition of Welsh Social Trends says that 340 of every 1,000
births were outside marriage in 1992 compared with 312 in England and Wales
as a whole. The rate is nearly nine times higher than it was 40 years ago.
Nearly half of all households in Wales were headed in 1992 by someone who
was economically inactive or unemployed. In 1991 average earnings for
full-time male workers were only 87 per cent of the British figure.
The report shows migration was the most important factor in population
change, overshadowing natural change. In recent years, most Welsh counties
have had net inflows of people and by 2011 the population is expected to
rise by 124,000 to 3.01m.
The number of people who speak Welsh has risen slightly since 1981, although
there were far fewer than before the second world war. In 1991 more than
500,000 people in the principality spoke Welsh, with the proportion of
children who were either fluent or could speak a 'fair amount' higher than
in the population as a whole.
Welsh Social Trends No. 9 1993. Statistical Publications Unit, SD5, Welsh
Office, Cathays Park, Cardiff CF1 3NQ. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
