<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Tories join Commons assault on army job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government came under heavy cross-party fire at Westminster yesterday
over a new round of army redundancies.
Tory backbenchers joined MPs from the leading opposition parties to attack
the 7,000 job losses made under the third phase of a redundancy programme to
reduce the size of the army.
There was particular concern about the prospect of redundancies among
officers and other ranks serving in Bosnia.
Downing Street officials said last night that the number of compulsory
redundancies among troops in Bosnia would 'only just' run into double
figures. Redundancies would be 'across the board'. It would be the same for
troops serving in Northern Ireland and elsewhere as it would be for those in
Bosnia.
Giving details of the cuts in a parliamentary written answer, Mr Jeremy
Hanley, armed forces minister, said tht the number of compulsory
redundancies would total just over 1,000. All those selected would be
notified today.
Mr Winston Churchill, a Tory member of the cross-party Commons defence
committee, said: 'We are strongly opposed, on an all-party committee basis,
to these cuts.'
Mr Churchill said the committee did not regard the cuts as inevitable. The
committee had 'called on the government last year not only to cease these
cuts but possibly to reverse them'.
He added: 'I happen to be opposed to all these redundancies, but the fact is
that if one is going to have redundancies it is regrettably impossible to be
selective as between those who happen at any moment to be in Northern
Ireland, the Falklands, Cyprus or, as the case may be, Bosnia.'
Mr David Clark, shadow defence secretary, said it was 'outrageous' that
British troops would be 'sacked' while they were risking their lives in
Bosnia.
The government was 'badly mismanaging British military forces'. What was
needed was a full defence review rather than 'arbitrary cuts imposed by the
Treasury'.
Mr Menzies Campbell, Liberal Democrat defence spokesman, said the cuts were
'foolish and insensitive'.
</TEXT>
