<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / M-way tolls to be levied from 1998
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 375 companies have responded to a call from the government for
proposals to develop an electronic tolling system for Britain's motorways.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, yesterday announced the timetable
for applications from companies to take part in trials. The government
intends that charging of tolls will start in 1998.
Ninety per cent of companies that had expressed an interest were British, Mr
MacGregor said. ICL, the Japanese-owned computer company, said it was
interested in taking part.
The cost of installing electronic equipment at the 700 motorway junctions
could exceed Pounds 100m, Mr MacGregor said. The trials would cost several
million pounds.
Many other countries are working on electronic tolls but none of them yet
has a system which could cope with the volumes of traffic on Britain's
motorways or with the features which the government wants to include.
The tolling system would have to work on motorways carrying up to 12,000
vehicles an hour at speeds of up to 70 mph without slowing traffic flow. It
would have to allow charges to be varied according to time of day and
vehicle type.
The government intends to install a fully electronic system with no facility
for motorists to pay cash. But it would have to take account of foreign
visitors and people making unplanned emergency trips.
One possibility is for a system of smart cards on vehicle windscreens which
would be 'read' by monitors on overhead gantries.
Toll booths common on Continental and US motorways have been rejected
because they require too much space and slow traffic.
The system chosen must be fraud-proof and allow the authorities to trace
motorists who travel without paying. However, the system must allow
motorists the option of choosing that their routes should not be traceable,
although there might be an extra charge for this.
France, Germany and Austria are soon to start limited tests of electronic
tolling. The British government is keen to introduce a system compatible
with other European Union members and holds regular discussions with French
and German officials.
The government has previously calculated that, if tolls were set at 1.5p a
mile for cars and 4.5p for trucks, tolling the 1,900 mile motorway network
would raise Pounds 700m a year.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Signpost to motorway charging
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Letter of invitation                                     February 1994
Closing date for application to participate and
return of questionnaire                                       May 1994
Closing date for system proposals                       September 1994
Selection of systems                                      January 1995
Track and on-road trials start                              March 1995
Final assessment of trials                               November 1995
Final system specification                                January 1996
Implementation starts                                             1998
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Department of Transport
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
