<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Funds pressed on asset strategies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK pension funds should broaden investment strategies away from equities to
reflect their rapidly increasing maturity, speakers told the Eastbourne
investment conference of the National Association of Pension Funds
yesterday.
But Mr Alastair Ross Goobey, a member of the Goode Committee on pension law
reform, denied that any shift towards fixed-interest bonds and other less
risky assets should be blamed on his committee's recommendation of a minimum
solvency standard.
'It is the age of the scheme that dictates asset allocation and not the
minimum solvency standard,' said Mr Ross Goobey, who is the chief executive
of PosTel, the manager of the British Telecom and Post Office pension funds.
He said it was contradictory that consulting actuaries who were warning of
the impact of a solvency standard were also attempting to persuade clients
to pay for asset-liability studies which would highlight the need to invest
in less volatile assets.
A consultant, Ms Meredith Brooks, of Frank Russell, said too few pension
schemes were taking sufficient notice of changes in their liability
structure. 'In my experience, a lot of pension fund trustees are quite
intimidated by fund managers,' she said.
Mr Terry Webb, a former IBM pension fund manager now with RGB International,
said that, so far, the asset-liability studies undertaken by UK pension
schemes had seldom resulted in a substantial modification to the investment
policies.
</TEXT>
