<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Selling weakens unit trust levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Private investors continued to pour money into unit trusts last month,
against a background of low interest rates, by investing a net Pounds 534m -
gross sales minus repurchases. However, heavy selling by institutions
reduced total net investment for January to Pounds 490m.
Both figures, issued yesterday by the Association of Unit Trust and
Investment Funds, are lower than December's, although the drop in retail
investment is only from Pounds 569m. Overall net investment was almost
halved from Pounds 895m. Private investors made net investments of Pounds
500m or more in August, October and December last year.
January's net retail investment represents a steep increase on January last
year, when private investors accounted for Pounds 112m of net sales. The
most popular retail funds last month were international growth and UK equity
income funds.
Repurchases in December from institutions, and to a lesser extent, private
investors, were high in the Far East, according to the association, which
attributed the reason to profit-taking after strong performance in the
region. The average Far East (excluding Japan) fund rose 86 per cent in
1993, according to HSW statistical information.
After falling out of favour in 1993, Japan became January's best-selling
fund with total net sales of Pounds 268m, of which Pounds 195m was due to
institutions and Pounds 73m from private investors.
Total gross sales of unit trusts last month were Pounds 1.94bn, and the
value of funds, at Pounds 99.9bn, was the highest recorded.
</TEXT>
