<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Code to be issued on profit forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A committee sponsored by the Stock Exchange will today issue a code of
conduct instructing directors that they should no longer privately correct
individual analysts' profits forecasts but should inform the entire market,
Norma Cohen and Robert Peston write.
Institutional investors and stockbrokers which receive unpublished price
sensitive information will also be advised to encourage companies to publish
the information widely.
The new code has been drawn up so that companies, shareholders and
stockbrokers can be confident they can communicate with each other without
infringing the provision of the Criminal Justice Act on insider trading,
which comes into force on Tuesday.
It has been drafted by representatives of the 100 Group of Finance
Directors, the Institutional Fund Managers Association and the Association
of British Insurers.
One member said the committee was particularly concerned about earnings
forecasts from analysts employed by a company's own stockbroker which 'have
been surprisingly accurate'.
</TEXT>
