<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Croats and Moslems agree Bosnia truce: Washington and Moscow
join in diplomatic drive to lay groundwork for a wider peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, ROBERT MAUTHNER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Croats and Moslems agreed a ceasefire yesterday as the US, Russia
and western Europe pressed ahead with efforts to lay the basis for peace in
Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The ceasefire, to start at 11 am GMT tomorrow, was announced by Mr Yasushi
Akashi, the United Nations envoy. It was agreed at UN-sponsored talks in
Zagreb between Mr Rasim Delic, commander of the Moslem-led Bosnian army, and
Mr Ante Roso, the Bosnian Croat military chief.
The accord appears a success for international efforts to build on the peace
arrangements for Sarajevo, where the threat of Nato air strikes combined
with Russian pressure has led to withdrawal of Serb artillery.
The Croats and Moslems agreed all heavy weapons would be handed over to UN
troops or withdrawn from battle fronts. Mortars will be pulled back 10km
from front lines, and tanks and heavy artillery 20km. UN troops will move in
to ensure compliance. If the truce holds in central Bosnia, it could pave
the way for lifting the Croat siege of Mostar, in western Hercegovina.
In their latest efforts, Washington, the UN, the European Union and Russia
are engaging in a three-pronged strategy aimed at creating a new peace plan
for Bosnia-Hercegovina, according to diplomats.
Under this strategy mediators are pressing for firm ceasefires in certain
regions, allowing unhindered access for humanitarian aid convoys and
eventual demilitarisation of the areas. But diplomats said success would
depend on a western commitment to send more peacekeepers to Bosnia - for
which omens are not good.
Mr Vitaly Churkin, Russian deputy foreign minister, and Mr Charles Redman,
US special envoy, held talks in Zagreb yesterday with Mr Thorvald
Stoltenberg and Lord Owen, the international peace negotiators. The talks
centred on Croatia and the Bosnian government agreeing to an eventual
'confederation' for Bosnia, following a ceasefire in central Bosnia and
lifting of the siege of Mostar.
US officials had hoped Germany would play a greater role in persuading
Croatia to pull its troops out of western Hercegovina. Mr Mate Granic,
Croatia's foreign minister, said yesterday Zagreb had withdrawn about 1,200
troops from western Hercegovina. But US officials said the pressure from
Bonn was not enough.
'It might be in the interests of the Moslems to sign up to a confederation,'
a Belgrade-based diplomat said. 'If not, they will be left with an unviable
state. If they are to have any hope of survival, the Moslems must make a
deal with either the Serbs or the Croats.'
This is where Washington's role is crucial, as part of the second prong to
the strategy. US and European leaders have told Bosnian president Alija
Izetbegovic they will help postwar reconstruction in an effort to win Moslem
endorsement of the diplomatic peace initiative. But Mr Izetbegovic is cool
largely because Croatia still refuses to withdraw its troops.
The third element involves the Russians, who can put pressure on the Serbs.
'Trying to coalesce these three elements of the strategy will be difficult,'
a British diplomat said, adding that pressure to capitalise on involvement
by Moscow and Washington must not be squandered.
Russian President Boris Yeltsin yesterday proposed an international summit
on Bosnia - an idea welcomed with caution by western nations.
</TEXT>
