<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / BT plans 'superhighway' services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications is set to announce a massive investment programme
aimed at creating 'information superhighways' capable of delivering a range
of inter-active video, banking and shopping services into homes across the
country.
The investment programme, the largest since the introduction of digital
exchanges in the mid-1980s, could involve replacing much of BT's local
'copper wire' networks with fibre-optics.
Estimates suggest the total outlay could exceed Pounds 10bn over more than a
decade, although large-scale investment would be unlikely to start for at
least three years. Dr Alan Rudge, BT's director of development and
procurement, told the FT yesterday an announcement about extending
fibre-optics to BT's local network was likely 'in the next few months.
'What we really want to do is to deliver services on demand - not just
video. We believe there is a much broader range of services which could be
delivered.'
As well as videos, shopping and banking, he cited estate and travel agency,
travel and holiday services and health and educational programmes as
important markets.
'There is no way we could justify an investment of this kind on just one
service,' he said, adding that the step required 'vision' but was little
different in kind from that taken for digitalisation in the early 1980s when
the costs 'looked horrendous'.
Most of BT's long-distance network is already fibre, but most of its local
network is copper, which has limited transmission capacity. Dr Rudge said BT
might be able to take fibre right into the home - not just to street level -
if the cost of the necessary electronics continued to fall.
BT's move comes on the back of similar announcements by US and Japanese
operators, who see consumer and public sector markets, not just business
demand, for new inter-active services. Last April NTT, the Japanese domestic
operator, announced plans to invest Dollars 396m to install fibre to all
subscribers by 2015.
Most of the US regional Bell operators have plans to extend fibre into their
local networks. Ameritech, which has 12m customers in the Midwest, last
month announced plans for a 'digital video network' extending to half its
network by the end of the decade. US West, which covers 14 western states,
earlier this month announced plans to build a hybrid fibre and coaxial
network.
BT hopes soon to offer a video service over existing copper wire, using
technology about to be piloted at Colchester in Essex.
But Dr Rudge said copper-based methods were only 'an interim solution'. Last
night BT said an initial trial with fibre-optics would take place in the
spring using the homes of 60 BT employees at Kesgrave, near Ipswich.
If it proved successful, the experiment would be extended to 2,500 BT
customers around the country, possibly in the autumn. The system might then
be introduced nationwide.
Nice benefits, what about the borders, Page 25
</TEXT>
