<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / France says'Non' to creeping franglais
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Balladur government yesterday stepped up its counter-offensive against
the incursions of English by announcing that it is considering legislation
to make the use of French compulsory in public advertising, announcements
and conferences, on radio and television and in work contracts.
The government has not yet decided what penalties to impose for the use of a
foreign word where a French equivalent exists and officials suggest the most
likely sanction would be removal of any public subsidy from the offending
organisation. The possibility of fines and even prison sentences has
apparently not been ruled out.
Considered in cabinet yesterday, the language bill will this spring go to
parliament, where last December deputies showed that, if anything, they were
more exercised than the government about the dilution of French culture.
MPs passed into law a requirement that by January 1996 all French radio
stations must bring the percentage of French songs in the music they
broadcast up to 40 per cent. That followed France's successful and
domestically popular attempt to prevent quotas for French films being
negotiated away in the Gatt talks, as the US had insisted.
Recently the legislators became a target when the secretary of the Academie
Francaise, guardian of the purity of the French language, complained to the
president of the National Assembly that MPs were using slipshod and improper
French in their debates.
The bill does not identify English explicitly as the culprit, but Mr Jacques
Toubon, the culture minister, did so yesterday in an interview in Le Monde
newspaper. 'Anglo-Saxon countries, far from contenting themselves by
passively benefiting from the situation of English . . . are deploying
considerable efforts . . . to conquer new territory for their language,' the
minister complained.
He has already publicly bridled at the decision by Eurotunnel, the
Anglo-French company, to dub its Channel tunnel train 'Le Shuttle' rather
'La Navette', and in yesterday's interview went on to warn that 'use of a
foreign language is not always innocent . . . it can become an instrument of
domination'.
Despite the efforts of the Academie Francaise to dream up French equivalents
to expressions such as 'le corner' kick in football, such franglais may
prove hard to stamp out. French businessmen find 'le cash flow' easier to
use than 'la marge brute d'autofinancement'.
But perhaps fining such franglais users will help the French government with
its own cash-flow problem, otherwise known as its deficit.
</TEXT>
