<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Poll shows Europe split on trade access
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH, European Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European business leaders favour reducing barriers to imports from east Asia
and eastern Europe and cutting government intervention to boost the
continent's long-term economic prospects, according to an opinion poll for
the Financial Times published today.
The survey of senior directors from 507 top European companies in seven
countries underlines the sluggish recovery from recession as well as
disappointment with the 1993 single market. Some 77 per cent of respondents
said they had registered no benefits from last year's measures to lower
Europe's internal trade barriers.
The poll, carried out by Harris Research for the FT and five other European
newspapers, highlights large divergences of opinion among executives in the
main European Union countries. While 55 per cent of respondents favour
easier access for imports from regions such as east Asia and eastern Europe,
26 per cent in France and 27 per cent in Spain want higher trade barriers.
The main points are:
40 per cent of respondents expect the EU economy to contract this year,
while 51 per cent expect growth of 1 per cent or less.
Only 10 per cent expect to increase staff in 1994, with 45 per cent planning
job cuts. British executives are far less enthusiastic about deepening EU
integration than on the Continent.
51 per cent of respondents think a single European currency would improve
competitiveness. German and UK executives are most sceptical.
The 'tiger' economies of east Asia, such as Korea and Taiwan, are seen as
the greatest threats to European industry.
German, Dutch and Belgian executives are particularly worried about
competition from eastern Europe.
Companies hold divergent views on measures to stimulate the economy. Some 51
per cent of German executives want tax cuts, while 63 per cent of UK
respondents want minimal EU involvement in the economy.
</TEXT>
