<PROFILE>_AN-EBWDCAGFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940223
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Government Bonds: Long-dated Treasuries advance after
testimony
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Longer-dated US Treasury bonds advanced yesterday after congressional
testimony by the Federal Reserve chairman produced no unpleasant surprises.
The price of short-dated paper was down slightly. Late in the session, the
benchmark 30-year government bond was  9/32 higher at 95 15/32 ,with the
yield slipping to 6.596 per cent. At the short end, the two-year note eased
 1/32 to 99, to yield 4.527 per cent.
The market's reaction to remarks by Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, was
restrained, in sharp contrast to the volatility of recent sessions.
In his twice-yearly Humphrey-Hawkins testimony on monetary policy, he told
lawmakers that real short-term interest rates were likely to increase, but
he gave no indication of the timing of the central bank's next move to lift
its target for the Fed Funds rate, now at 3.25 per cent.
Mr Greenspan stressed, however, that a failure to tighten 'in a timely
manner' would lead to an unnecessary rise in long-term rates on the
financial markets.
Despite his vigilant tone on inflation, long-term bond prices fell during
the first hour of testimony. When a significant sell-off failed to
materialise, however, the market quickly reversed course.
After several false starts, the long bond pushed well into positive
territory during the afternoon. The short end, however, remained weak.
Amid the attention focused on the Fed chairman's comments, a
bigger-than-expected decline in consumer confidence this month went largely
unnoticed.
The Conference Board, an industry association, said its index fell to 80.8
for February, from a revised 82.6 in January, and compared with a consensus
forecast of 83.
In Europe, bond markets stabilised after their recent sharp falls, but
trading conditions remained volatile. While some traders reported cautious
buying by professional investors, most said activity remained thin.
According to Mr Keith Edmonds, chief analyst at IBJ International, the
European bond markets are beginning to build a base from which they can
rally. 'Now that Treasuries have begun to stabilise, the European markets
can focus again on their own fundamentals, allowing them to push ahead,' he
said.
Most observers expect a sustainable European bond market recovery to be
triggered by the next cut in the Bundesbank's rate for securities repurchase
agreements. The rate has again been fixed at 6 per cent for today's repo
allocation, but is expected to fall once the wage talks in the German
engineering sector have been resolved.
Like most European markets, UK gilts had a rollercoaster session. The short
end came under pressure following a report from the UK Treasury panel of
advisers, known as the six wise men, which showed divisions over the need
for further cuts in interest rates.
The long end of the yield curve strengthened slightly, supported by
continental European markets. Nevertheless, gilts underperformed bunds, with
the 10-year spread over Germany widening to 90 basis points from 85 basis
points on Monday.
The market's firmer tone boosted hopes that today's auction of Pounds 2.5bn
of 7 per cent gilts due 2001 would go smoothly.
German government bonds ended a volatile session slightly higher. In
after-hours trading the bund future rose further to close near the day's
high of 97.95, up from 97.36 on Monday.
Traders now are awaiting January M3 money supply numbers, expected this
week. Although most traders expect them to lie above the Bundesbank's target
range, 'a bad number could cause a kneejerk sell-off,' said one dealer.
French bonds ended little changed, in line with most other markets. The
notional long bond futures contract on Matif closed at 127.54, up 0.02
point.
Japanese government bonds firmed in Tokyo and continued to strengthen in
London as speculation of a cut in the 1.75 per cent official discount rate
intensified. Easing talk was fuelled by the release of a worse-than-expected
diffusion index and the announcement that the Bank of Japan will publish its
quarterly Tankan economic report on March 1, earlier than expected.
The June JGB futures contract rose 0.14 point to 112.39 in Tokyo but rose
further to 112.80 in late London trading.
</TEXT>
