<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / International Company News: Year-end boosts Morgan Stanley
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Morgan Stanley, the US investment bank, yesterday reported a 28 per cent
increase in fourth-quarter profits to Dollars 181.2m, following strong
contributions from its investment banking and securities trading businesses.
The final quarter took profits for the fiscal year 1993 to Dollars 786.1m,
compared with Dollars 510.5m the previous year.
Net revenues for the final quarter were up 33 per cent to Dollars 925.4m,
and for the full year up 38 per cent to Dollars 4.16bn.
In the latest quarter, Morgan Stanley's principal trading business - trading
securities for itself and its customers - was especially strong, with
revenues rising 83 per cent to Dollars 286.1m.
During the year, the bank said results from customer-related global
fixed-income and equity businesses and commodities and foreign exchange
trading were particularly positive.
Investment banking revenue in the fourth quarter rose only 7.5 per cent to
Dollars 244.9m, but over the year it increased 28 per cent to Dollars
1.24bn, as debt and equity underwriting volume and growth in demand for
financial and advisory services both rose.
Among its merchant banking deals during 1993, Morgan Stanley singled out the
revenues generated by the initial public offering of Southern Pacific
Railroad and the second offering of Kohl's Corporation stock.
Commission revenues in the quarter rose 35 per cent to Dollars 110.1m, and
earnings from asset management and administration climbed 54 per cent to
Dollars 74.8m.
On the cost side, non-interest expenses rose 35 per cent in the three months
to Dollars 677.7m, due primarily to a sharp rise in employee compensation
payments, which are linked to the firm's profitability.
Morgan Stanley also announced an 11 per cent increase in its regular
quarterly dividend to 30 cents, and plans for an additional Dollars 150m
buy-back of common stock.
During fiscal 1993, the firm strengthened its capital base through issues of
new long-term debt and convertible preferred stock. As of January 31, its
capital stood at Dollars 9.8bn.
Yesterday's results had little impact upon the bank's share price, which was
unchanged at Dollars 70 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
