<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Provisions cut helps Bradford &amp; Bingley
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bradford &amp; Bingley building society, the UK's eighth largest, yesterday
reported a 47 per cent rise in pre-tax profits from Pounds 91.3m to Pounds
134.3m for the year to end-December.
The result was helped by a steep fall in provisions for bad and doubtful
debts, from Pounds 81m to Pounds 43.7m, which the society said was a result
of lower interest rates and a slight improvement in the housing market.
However, it has also set aside about Pounds 5m against possible liabilities
as a result of its 6,000 pension transfer cases.
Total mortgage lending was down slightly, to Pounds 1.8bn (Pounds 1.9bn). Mr
John Smith, finance director, said that reflected both the strong
competition in the mortgage market, and the society's tightening of its
lending criteria and refusal to carry out uneconomic lending.
Despite the strong competition for retail savings, net retail savings
receipts were Pounds 348m - about 16 per cent of the building societies'
savings market. The percentage of wholesale funds fell from 25.6 per cent to
23.7 per cent.
Income from the society's financial planning business - it is an independent
financial adviser - rose by 20 per cent from Pounds 25.7m to Pounds 30.9m.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at UBS, said the results were in line
with the 'bounce-back' of the sector as a whole after the difficulties
caused by the levels of bad debts in recent years. He added that the results
were particularly impressive because the growth followed 'reasonable'
results last year as well.
Administrative expenses rose to Pounds 154m (Pounds 139.6m) and operating
profits came through at Pounds 178m (Pounds 172.3m).
Assets grew by 6.3 per cent from Pounds 13bn to Pounds 13.9bn.
Coventry Building Society achieved a 30 per cent rise in pre-tax profits
from Pounds 24.7m to Pounds 32.1m in the year to December 31.
The advance was largely because of a fall in mortgage arrears which enabled
the society to cut provisions by 60 per cent to Pounds 5.5m. The pre-tax
result was after a Pounds 1.2m exceptional charge for management
reorganisation.
The society's assets grew by 10 per cent to Pounds 2.97bn.
Pre-tax profits of the Newcastle Building Society rose by 6 per cent from
Pounds 13.1m to Pounds 13.9m in 1993, after a fall in provisions for loans
and advances to Pounds 1.62m (Pounds 2.13m).
Total assets increased by 10 per cent to Pounds 1.19bn (Pounds 1.08bn).
</TEXT>
