<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Hanson to raise Dollars 1bn via convertible
bond offering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hanson, the Anglo-American conglomerate, intends to raise Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 600m) through one of the largest-ever international convertible bond
offerings.
The company said the proceeds of the offering, which will be issued by its
indirect, wholly-owned subsidiary Hanson America, would be used to retire
existing bank debt.
Bankers involved in arranging the widely-expected offering said the funds
raised would partly refinance the expensive debt which Hanson inherited when
it bought Quantum Chemical Corporation last year.
They added that the structure of the deal, which is being arranged by Lehman
Brothers, provided Hanson with a tax-efficient way to finance its US
operations.
Last week, Hanson announced plans to complete the refinancing of Quantum's
Dollars 2.35bn (Pounds 1.6bn) worth of junk bond debt. The company is to
redeem three bond issues on March 15 with a total of Dollars 900m
outstanding, which were paying an average interest rate of 11.4 per cent. It
redeemed Dollars 1.15bn of bonds at the end of October last year and bought
Dollars 300m of bonds in the market. Altogether this debt bore an average
rate of 11 per cent.
The new bonds, which are exchangeable into Hanson's American depositary
shares, are likely to have a current yield of about three per cent. But
since the bonds will be issued at a relatively deep discount to par, their
yield to maturity is likely to be between 5 1/4 and 5 3/4 per cent.
The bonds are expected to have a maturity of seven years and carry a
conversion premium of between 20 to 22 per cent. Yesterday Hanson's ADSs
traded at Dollars 20 3/8 , down  5/8 on the day.
See Euromarkets
</TEXT>
