<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Council tendering target reduced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday announced a scaling down of its ambitious plans for
exposing local authority services to private sector competition.
English metropolitan councils will be required to put out to competitive
tender 65 per cent of their white-collar construction services, rather than
the 90 per cent ministers proposed in 1992.
The Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities claimed the
reduction in competitive tendering for construction was the result of
'pressure from local authorities', and said it would attempt to reduce the
figure still further during consultation, which lasts until May.
Mr Tony Baldry, the environment minister, said the proposals, announced in a
consultation paper, were the result of 'frank, positive and useful
discussions between central and local government'.
The construction services are architecture, engineering, surveying and
valuation, which account for a total budget of more than Pounds 1m. They
will be the first white-collar services compulsorily exposed to competition
under the government's competitive tendering programme. The 90 per cent
target was to have applied for all white-collar services.
A series of separate exemptions for small councils and for those that have
recently started large projects means that many authorities will be required
to market-test much less than 65 per cent of their services when competitive
tendering becomes compulsory in October next year.
Authorities will also be free not to take the cheapest bid; they can make
their own judgments about the trade-off between quality and cost, provided
the procedures are 'fair and even-handed'.
However, local authorities in England and Wales will have to publish
accounts to enable the costs of their services to be compared with others.
Mr Baldry said he assumed comparisons would 'identify the best and stimulate
the rest'.
Officials made clear that they would not publish the data in the form of
'league tables'. It will appear as a memorandum to council accounts, and
will be subject to audit.
The new statements of support service and costs will be introduced next year
for legal and construction-related services and will later be extended to
cover information technology, finance, personnel and administration.
They must show the total cost of each service to the council  - whether it
has been provided by private contractors or in-house  - and how much has
been charged to other council departments for use of services.
Councils reacted negatively, with Mr Jeremy Beecham, leader of
Labour-controlled Newcastle city council, saying the new statements would be
'bureaucratic, time-consuming and expensive to prepare'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
