<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Telecoms are high in world ranking: BT charges most for
domestic use, says DTI survey of advanced nations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's telecommunications rank a 'a good second' internationally, says a
government study comparing telecoms in the UK with those in six other
advanced countries.
The study - comparing everything from prices to network modernisation - does
not find the UK the most advanced in any sphere, though no one country was
consistently better. The US scored higher on many counts.
Britain was found to have the most expensive residential calls of any of the
seven countries, however, with average charges almost twice those in Sweden
and the Netherlands.
The figures were based on British Telecommunications charges as at January
1992. Its prices are now undercut in parts of the residential market by
Mercury and the cable companies. BT has cut residential prices sharply since
1992 - but so have companies in the other six countries.
The study, part of the exercise in rating UK industrial sectors against
those of other countries that was launched by the Department of Trade and
Industry last year, was hailed by the government as support for its policy
of liberalising telecommunications infrastructure and services faster than
the rest of the EU.
The UK will soon have three long-distance telecoms networks and cable
companies - mainly US-owned - are investing nearly Pounds 5bn in building
local TV and telephone networks in competition with BT.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said: 'Competition in
telecoms infrastructure as well as services has played a large part in
stimulating the adoption of leading-edge technology in UK networks.'
The report, compiled by Mr Robert Harrison of PA Consulting Group, found
Britain was fourth out of seven in deployment of fibre cable in the core
network, the essential requirement for broadband services of the kind
envisaged by proponents of a 'superhighway' that would offer advanced
interactive services.
Figures for investment in the network also provide an ambiguous picture.
Britain is ranked behind Germany, Japan and the US in terms of investment
per line, but comes out second behind the US when the figures are adjusted
for price and specification of equipment.
The UK scored highly in the provision of digital lines, enabling the
provision of advanced network services, where it was ranked second behind
France; and also in the take-up of cellular mobile services, where it is on
a par with the US although still some way behind Sweden.
The report noted a view 'held by some in the industry' that a 'clearer
vision' was needed of national telecoms objectives. It also said an issue of
concern was the poor regard in which telecoms services were widely held in
the UK.
</TEXT>
