<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Growth figure for end of last year revised upwards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Economic growth in the fourth quarter of last year was slightly stronger
than previously estimated, with gross domestic product increasing by a
seasonally adjusted 0.8 per cent, up from the earlier estimate of 0.7 per
cent.
Figures released by the Central Statistical Office yesterday showed that for
last year as a whole GDP was 2 per cent higher than in 1992. If oil and gas
are excluded, the rise in GDP was 1.7 per cent, down from the 1.8 per cent
previously estimated.
Economic output in the fourth quarter of last year was 2.6 per cent higher
than in the same period of 1992. If oil and gas are excluded the increase
was 2.2 per cent.
Construction output, which was previously seen as flat in the fourth
quarter, is estimated as having risen by about 1 per cent between the third
and fourth quarters. This factor is mainly responsible for the upgrading of
fourth-quarter GDP growth.
The figures give a more detailed breakdown of the economy than was available
in the preliminary GDP estimate, published in January. They show that
stockbuilding played a substantial part in fourth-quarter growth, with the
value of stocks rising by Pounds 597m.
Capital spending by manufacturers was flat in the fourth quarter and 2 per
cent lower than in the same period of 1992. Gross domestic fixed capital
formation fell 0.3 per cent between the fourth quarters of 1992 and last
year.
The statistics show that one measure of inflation, the GDP deflator, is
gathering pace. According to the CSO the deflator rose by 3.5 per cent for
last year as a whole, the lowest annual rise since 1968. In the fourth
quarter, however, the deflator rose 1.7 per cent and was 4.5 per cent higher
than in the same period of 1992.
The GDP deflator is calculated after subtracting the effect of import
prices. Since import prices have been falling, this indicates that
home-based inflation is higher than shown by other measures.
Analysts differed on the importance of the deflator. Mr Robert Barrie of
Barclays de Zoete Wedd said it was a sign that companies had been increasing
their margins with price increases. Mr Simon Briscoe of SG Warburg
Securities pointed to the poor quality of the trade statistics, which are
used to calculate the GDP deflator. He said the consumers' expenditure
deflator, which was growing at an annual rate of only 3 per cent in the
fourth quarter, was a better indicator of inflationary pressures.
One sign of improved company margins was a 22.9 per cent rise in the gross
trading profits of companies last year. Profits in the fourth quarter were
26.9 per cent higher than in the same period of 1992.
The gross trading surplus of public corporations rose 50.1 per cent between
1992 and last year. The CSO said this rise might have been caused by the
addition of new entities to the sector, such as National Health Service
trusts.
Meanwhile, income from employment rose 2.9 per cent between 1992 and last
year, the lowest growth rate recorded since the series started in 1948.
</TEXT>
