<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Faster inquiries aim to cut years off road building
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday gave details of proposals aimed at shortening the
time taken for public inquiries into new road schemes.
With recent measures to reduce the length of the planning process, the
effect of the proposed changes could be to cut total time taken to plan and
build new roads from an average of 13 years to only eight, the transport
department said.
The government hopes to have the new rules in place by the summer after a
three-month period for public consultation, Mr John MacGregor, transport
secretary, said in a Commons written answer.
The main changes to the rules are:
Giving a formal standing to pre-inquiry meetings so that contentious issues
can be resolved early. Allowing the inspector to set a timetable for the
inquiry in advance. Requiring statements of evidence to be presented and
exchanged before the inquiry.
Allowing the inspector to study long statements before an inquiry with only
summaries read out at proceedings.
Giving inspectors the right to refuse evidence they believe to be irrelevant
or repetitious.
The new rules would apply in England and Wales only. Scotland already has a
'fast tracking' procedure to speed roadbuilding programmes.
'These measures will bring highway inquiry rules into line with other
planning inquiries while stopping deliberate attempts to slow their
progress,' Mr MacGregor said.
'These tactics have in the past led to the waste of time and taxpayers'
money,' he added, saying the new proposals would not diminish objectors'
rights.
Public inquiries form only part of the planning process but they can lead to
substantial delays in roadbuilding. The extension to the M3 motorway at
Twyford Down in Hampshire took 25 years before work started and involved
three public inquiries.
The M11 extension in east London, recently the subject of battles between
police and protestors, also required three public inquiries. The new rules
would not reduce the number of inquiries but should reduce their length.
The British Road Federation welcomed the planned changes but said they would
work only as part of a wider package including steps to cut delays within
the Department of Transport, more generous compensation payments and
increased public involvement at an early stage in roadbuilding.
Mr Richard Diment, director of the federation, said: 'Britain's current
planning laws are a recipe for blight and cannot deliver the quality
transport system our country needs.'
</TEXT>
