<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Drugs policy 'watered down'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's policy on illegal drugs was under attack yesterday after
leaked papers showed it had altered a report calling for a coherent approach
to drug misuse.
Two versions of a report by the Department of Health show the original paper
containing criticism of the government's failure to provide a co-ordinated
drugs policy.
In the final version the title have been changed, key texts calling for a
new partnership to tackle the problem in local communities have been watered
down, and some chapters have been omitted.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said: 'The first version of the report
that has been with the Department of Health for over a year is strongly
critical of government policy and urges precisely the type of new strategy
to fight drug misuse that Labour proposes.'
Mr Blair said: 'These two versions are drastically different with every sign
that hard-hitting recommendations have been deliberately watered down.'
The government yesterday said the report had been changed because the
management consultants, Roger Howard Associates, who had been commissioned
to write the report had gone 'well beyond their brief'.
Labour is pushing for an amendment to the criminal justice bill to tackle
the link between drug abuse and youth crime.
