<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Lobbyists cool to self-regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Five of the largest lobbying firms have teamed up to produce proposals for a
self-regulating regime for the industry. But they told MPs yesterday that
they would rather be regulated by parliament.
Mr Michael Burrell, managing director of Westminster Strategy, told MPs on
the committee of members' interests that the suggestions were only the
second-best approach.
Self-regulation could lead to a perception that the industry was acting as
judge and jury, he said.
He added that a system similar to the register of members' interests, which
records pecuniary interests and other material benefits received by MPs,
would 'command more respect' than anything the industry could put forward.
The five firms - Westminster Strategy, European Political Consultancy Group,
GJW Government Relations, Ian Greer Associates and The Public Policy Unit -
are proposing to set up a Association of Political Consultants. The five
account for at least Pounds 10m of turnover between them.
This body would propose a code of professional practice and impose a number
of ethical duties on its members. It would be responsible for disciplining
its members should the code of practice be breached.
It would also maintain a voluntary register of professional lobbyists. The
firms said: 'We believe that the voluntary principle would avoid the
administrative complications associated with such a wide remit while
highlighting those who refuse to register.'
Referring to alternative proposals under which the Public Relations
Consultants Association would administer a registration system and code of
conduct for lobbyists, the firms said it would be 'inappropriate' for a body
representing the public relations industry to regulate professional
lobbyists.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, has said a voluntary code of
registration would be preferable to a register that was imposed.
</TEXT>
