<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Major urges US to bar Adams
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major will use his visit to the US next week to urge President Bill
Clinton to reject any new request from Mr Gerry Adams to visit the US unless
the Sinn Fein president renounces the use of violence by the IRA.
Amid signs that Mr Clinton is reluctant to allow Mr Adams a repeat of his
public relations triumph in New York earlier this month, British officials
said Mr Major would stress the potential damage to the UK-Irish peace
initiative.
After his talks last weekend with Mr Albert Reynolds, the Irish prime
minister, Mr Major will stress that there are no differences between the
approach of London and Dublin in efforts to secure a settlement in Northern
Ireland.
The officials said Mr Major would emphasise that this approach - and the
resultant pressure on the IRA and Sinn Fein to renounce violence - would be
undermined if Mr Adams were again given permission to visit the US.
It is understood that Washington has offered private assurances to Downing
Street that the differences over Mr Adams' visit do not represent a
fundamental shift in US policy. That view has been echoed by US officials
who acknowledged that the failure of Mr Adams to embrace December's
Anglo-Irish declaration during his New York trip caused considerable
disappointment in the White House.
Officials are less confident, however, that Mr Major and Mr Clinton will
find it as easy to smooth transatlantic frictions over the west's approach
to the Bosnian war. In spite of the success of the Nato initiative to lift
the siege of Sarajevo, officials on both sides of the Atlantic believe there
is still a considerable risk of further disputes over the war.
Britain's demand that the US commit ground troops to the UN operation in
Bosnia has been met with a flat rejection in Washington. For its part the
London government remains unconvinced that the Clinton administration is
ready to put pressure on the Bosnian government to reach a settlement with
the Serbs.
US officials said the Bosnian issue had become a test of Nato's new role
after the end of the cold war, raising fears that further disputes could
undermine Washington's long-term commitment to European security.
Mr Major hopes that the form of his visit next week - he will stay overnight
at the White House - will put to rest recent talk of a permanent Anglo-US
rift.
</TEXT>
