<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Standard Life likely to accept new watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Standard Life, one of the UK's leading insurers, is almost certain to sign
up for the proposed new financial services watchdog in spite of its earlier
preference for full statutory regulation.
Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director and a former board member of the
proposed Personal Investment Authority, said there was only 'an outside
chance' that the company would reject the PIA and insist on being regulated
directly by the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog.
He resigned as a PIA director in January over the decision that people
working in the financial services industry should not make up a majority of
the board, but yesterday
highlighted the Treasury's commitment that the PIA should come into
existence.
'We will make the best of life the way it is,' he said. 'We will certainly
not be making futile gestures.'
Mr Stretton added that the only basis on which Standard Life would seek to
be SIB-regulated was if it was clear that the PIA faced 'masses of
opposition and a community of view (in the industry) about what should
happen'.
While his comments will be welcomed by the PIA, his view that the
establishment of the new regulator did not mean the end of the argument
about the direction of regulation is likely to be less welcome.
He also highlighted the PIA's costs - involving 18 per cent fee increases -
and its streamlined committee structure, which omits a general 'practitioner
panel', as two elements likely to cause concern.
There were signs of more vigorous opposition to the PIA from the National
Federation of Independent Financial Advisers which intends today to compare
the PIA prospectus with its own charter of seven consumers' rights. It is
already clear that the prospectus will not measure up in all respects.
</TEXT>
