<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Life policies head complaints league
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Life assurance was the biggest source of complaints dealt with by the
insurance ombudsman last year with the most common allegations being
maladministration, poor communication and mis-selling.
About 39 per cent of life assurance complaints were upheld compared with 29
per cent for general insurance. 'The difference does perhaps underline some
of the difficulties involved in satisfactory selling of investment products
to the public,' said Mr Julian Farrand, the ombudsman, in his annual report.
Responsibility for handling many life assurance complaints will pass to the
ombudsman for the new Personal Investment Authority later this year. But the
maximum compulsory award in the PIA scheme will be Pounds 50,000, whereas
the insurance ombudsman can oblige companies to pay up to Pounds 100,000.
Complaints about home income plans sold in the 1980s, when many elderly
people were encouraged to take the risky step of mortgaging their homes and
investing the proceeds to provide an income, form a large part of the
current workload.
Companies were required to pay out Pounds 7.4m last year as a result of the
ombudsman's adjudications. The largest single payment was Pounds 230,000 and
the smallest Pounds 3.88.
</TEXT>
