<HEADLINE>
FT  23 FEB 94 / Trade boost for Paris and Bonn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France and Germany achieved sharp increases in their trade surpluses last
year as recession in both countries smothered imports and more than
compensated for falling exports.
The French customs office yesterday reported a record FFr87.3bn (Pounds
10bn), double official forecasts.
Germany's surplus nearly doubled to DM59.4bn (Pounds 23bn) as imports fell
more sharply than exports in the worst domestic recession since the second
world war.
The French surplus reflected the impact of recession, which contributed to a
10.4 per cent fall in imports to FFr1,091bn. It also showed the resilience
of exports which declined by just over 5 per cent to FFr1,181bn despite
depressed demand in Germany and the negative effect of currency depreciation
in Italy, Spain and the UK.
significan
Germany exports fell for the year by 10 per cent to DM603.5bn while imports
decreased by 14.7 per cent to DM544.1bn, according to statistical office
figures. Both imports and exports recorded their sharpest decline since the
war.
The current account deficit was reduced to DM36bn from DM39bn the previous
year.
</TEXT>
