FT  22 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Greece being too quickly criticised
over Macedonia (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr NIKOS CHLOROS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your editorial, 'Greek disgrace' (February 18), has left at least one
Greek reader quite unhappy. Your paper has been too quick to chastise the
Greek presidency for the 'affront' to its EU partners on the subject of the
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM). I ask you, who can forget the
recent diplomatic blunder both Britain and Germany committed by visiting
Turkey without even notifying their Greek partners?
How are Greece's EU partners justified in, on the one hand, condemning the
country's consistent foreign policies regarding FYROM and, on the other,
praising its history and heritage that form the basis of the modern western
civilisation? It is, after all, this history and heritage that Greece wishes
to defend from the usurpers of the Vergina flag and the Macedonian name.
Stabilisation in the region is, indeed, in Greece's interests and everybody
hopes for a quick solution on the FYROM problem. However, fuelling EU
impatience and 'intense irritation with Greece' and suggesting what the best
strategy should be 'for a country so heavily dependent on EU funds' do not,
in my opinion, represent constructive criticism.
Inflammatory comments and the passing of such judgment do not fit the
serious profile of your paper.
Nikos Chloros,
