<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Germany escaping stranglehold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr HOLGER SCHMIEDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your stimulating leading article, 'In Germany, it may get worse'
(February 15), seems to portray the looming labour dispute in west German
metal engineering as a threat to a possible recovery. However, it could also
be seen as the birth pangs of a most beneficial revolution.
The labour market is finally escaping the traditional stranglehold of big
labour organisations and big business. The profound change is driven by west
Germany's deepest postwar recession, a structural shift from industry to
less unionised services and a growing awareness of the disaster that
Germany's corporatist organisations caused in east Germany with excessive
wage accords.
This January's pilot agreement in the west German chemicals sector not only
delivered an effective wage increase of 2 percentage points below current
inflation. It did away with more labour market taboos than even the most
ardent optimists had hoped for. The 35-40 hour corridor for the working
week, more leeway from bargaining at company level, and lower wages for
long-term unemployed re-entering the labour market are among the
achievements.
Even IG Metall, once the most powerful union in the non-communist world, has
yielded a lot. It may still try to fight a lamentable rearguard action
against the trend. But if it indeed took an open conflict to clear the way
for a more flexible and efficient labour market, the economy should emerge
stronger rather than weaker from it - apart, of course, from a short-term
dip in a quarterly gross domestic product growth rate. And even if, for
whatever reason, the final settlement in metal engineering would not deliver
the needed extra flexibility, the change would most likely come about
nonetheless.
The present stream of companies leaving the employers' association and
striking their own tailor-made deals with the workforce would probably swell
to a flood, making the outdated central bargaining ritual more and more
obsolete.
Holger Schmieding,
senior economist,
Merrill Lynch Bank AG,
Frankfurt/Main,
Germany
</TEXT>
