<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: High cost of share options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr C W DAWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Whatever views one may hold about share option schemes, one thing
should be made clear. They are not costing large amounts of lost tax - quite
the opposite.
Most directors who exercise high-value share options will sell the shares
immediately. So the director who realises a gain of Pounds 1m will be
subject to 40 per cent capital gains tax on virtually all the gain, just as
he would have paid 40 per cent income tax on a Pounds 1m bonus.
The director's gain is the company's loss. The shareholders will lose value
of Pounds 1m just as surely as if the company had paid a bonus of the same
amount to the director. The vital difference is that the bonus payment earns
a corporation tax recovery of Pounds 330,000, making a net cost of Pounds
670,000, whereas the cost deriving from the share option gets no such
relief. So share options are a much more expensive way of delivering value
to directors than cash bonus schemes. The only reason share option schemes
persist is because the cost to shareholders does not appear in the profit
and loss account, or indeed anywhere else in the accounts, and it is only
through the newspapers that some of the largest figures are revealed.
If shareholders really appreciated what share option schemes are costing
them, particularly in terms of extra tax, they would close the schemes
overnight and replace them with cash bonus schemes.
C W Daws,
Church Commissioners,
1 Millbank,
London SW1P 3JZ
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
