<DOCNO>FT941-7939</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EBVDKAHBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940222
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Producer David Munro and reporter John Pilger (who made the memorable
Cambodia Year Zero) entered East Timor as tourists and shot secretly on
camcorders to make tonight's extended Network First documentary (10.40 ITV).
Then they had to smuggle the tapes out.
More than 200,000 people are said to have died since Indonesia invaded East
Timor in 1975. Munro and Pilger have investigated a mass killing at a
cemetery in 1991 and especially the subsequent events: it seems that
survivors were tracked down and killed, even those in hospital.
Given the number of impressive actors around, it is not clear why Oliver
Reed was chosen as the subject of the spoof obituary slot on Without Walls
(9.00 C4). A better idea is the item in which writer Paul Bailey accuses
'celebrity chefs' of promoting 'cuisine elitism' (9.30).
With reference to crime in general and the James Bulger murder in
particular, 40 Minutes asks 'Why blame the mother?' (9.50 BBC2). Omnibus
looks at the work of Damien Hirst (10.25 BBC1).
</TEXT>
