<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / People: Goldman Sachs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Michael Sherwood, the larger-than-life syndicate manager who surprised the
Eurobond market last month when he left Goldman Sachs for a quieter life as
a fund manager at a private Swiss bank, has missed the buzz of the City so
much that he has asked for his old job back.
And Goldman's top brass, eternally grateful to 'Woody' for taking the bank
to the top of the Eurobond league table last year, have welcomed him back
with open arms. No doubt they will look favourably on him when they award
partnerships in November.
Sherwood will be back at his old haunt today and will be joined on the
syndicate desk by Noel Dunn, an executive director of the firm. Sion
Kearsey, who valiantly held the fort during Sherwood's absence, has also
been rewarded. He has been named joint head of Eurobond trading with Chris
Pigden.
</TEXT>
