<HEADLINE>
FT  22 FEB 94 / Planner warns against 'loosening green belts'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Guidelines to strengthen the green belts of rural land encircling some of
the largest cities were published yesterday by the government.
The consultation document was greeted warily by environmentalists, who fear
that the proposals could encourage more development.
Mr Tony Burton, senior planner at the Council for the Protection of Rural
England, said: 'The government's tinkering with these rules risks loosening
the green belt.'
Green belts are areas around cities in which permission for new development
is tightly restricted. Local authorities are obliged to take the
government's guidelines into account when preparing development plans.
Mr David Curry, planning minister, launching the revised draft of the
planning policy guidance on green belts yesterday, said: 'The changes we
have made to the original guidance note are designed to . . . (make) greater
allowances for environmental and economic factors and to (address) practical
difficulties in operating it.'
Mr Curry added that research conducted for the Department of the Environment
last year concluded that the rural appearance of land within the green belts
was being upheld.
Publication of the document follows an attack by Mr John Gummer, environment
secretary, on 'urban sprawl' and the construction of new shopping centres
outside towns.
The consultation paper wants 'to permit existing buildings in the green belt
to be re-used, whether or not they are redundant, subject to stringent
safeguards'. It also recommends that local authorities be allowed to re-use
'pre-war factories and power stations'.
The CPRE fears this could open the door to more development of derelict
sites in rural areas. It also accused the report of drawing green-belt
boundaries too loosely around urban areas.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour environment spokesman, said: 'The government's
failure to bring in a register of contaminated land, coupled with
uncertainty (among bankers, insurers and developers) about the exact
situation on liability for pollution means that people have no encouragement
to develop derelict land in urban areas.'
Draft revision of Planning Policy Guidance Note 2, Green Belts. DoE, Room
C13/11 2 Marsham St, London SW1 3EB.
</TEXT>
